VIRAL GASTROENTERITIS UPDATE 2002 - UK & IRELAND(03)
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[The outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis included in these updates have the
characteristics of "winter vomiting disease," and are presumed to be caused
by Norwalk-like viruses (i.e., caliciviruses classified in the genus
_Norovirus_), although this is rarely confirmed microbiologically. The UK
and Ireland seem to be particularly prone at present to outbreaks of
"winter-vomiting" disease in institutional settings. - Mod.CP]
In these updates:
[1] UK versus US experience
[2] England (Epsom)
[3] Scotland (Glasgow)
******
[1]
Date: Tue 29 Oct 2002
From: Jon Rosenberg (DHS-DCDC-DISB-DI)" <JRosenbe@dhs.ca.gov>

Norwalk-like virus in Healthcare Facilities, U.S. versus U.K.
-----------------------------------------------
In a recent comment to the ProMED-mail post entitled "Norwalk-like virus,
cruise ship - USA (Florida) 20021026.5642" the moderator stated "It is
intriguing that the reports of Norwalk-like virus infection from North
America relate predominantly to food-borne outbreaks and outbreaks in
recreational settings, whereas the reports from Europe, and the UK in
particular, concern outbreaks in health-care establishments and schools."
While this may reflect a predilection on the part of U.S. reports to focus
on foodborne and recreational setting outbreaks, the real epidemiological
difference between the U.S. and the U.K. appears to be in the type of
healthcare facility affected by NLVs: in the U.K. hospitals and nursing
homes or other residential care facilities appear to be equally affected,
while in the U.S., nursing home outbreaks are relatively common, but
outbreaks in hospitals are rarely reported.
Recent ProMED reports have documented significant NLV outbreaks in
hospitals in the U.K. From 1992 to 2000 The Public Health Laboratory
Service Communicable Disease Surveillance Centre received reports of 1877
laboratory confirmed outbreaks of NLV infection in England and Wales,
affecting 57 000 people, 24 of whom died. There were 754 outbreaks in
hospitals, 724 outbreaks in residential care homes, 147 outbreaks in
hotels, 105 restaurants, and 73 in schools. In 85 percent of cases the mode
of transmission was person-to-person spread, and only 10 percent were
foodborne. (PHLS. Outbreaks of Norwalk-like virus infection. Commun Dis Rep
CDR Weekly 24 Jan 2002
<http://www.phls.org.uk/publications/cdr/archive02/News/news0402.html#Norwalk>).
Presumably as a reflection of the importance of NLV outbreaks in hospitals
in the U.K., a guide to their management was recently published (Chadwick
PR, Beards G, Brown D, et al. Report of the Public Health Laboratory
Service Viral Gastroenteritis Working Group. Management of hospital
outbreaks of gastro-enteritis due to small round structured viruses. J Hosp
Infect (2000) 45: 1-10.
<http://www.phls.co.uk/topics_az/norwalk/hospital_srsv.pdf>).
In contrast, CDC examined 90 outbreaks of non-bacterial gastroenteritis
reported to 33 state health departments from Jan 1996 to Jun 1997, for
which it found NLVs by PCR in 86. Nursing homes were the most frequent
setting, accounting for 43 percent of the outbreaks and apparently all of
the healthcare facility outbreaks. Restaurants and events with catered
meals accounted for only 26 percent, and vacation settings (including
cruise ships) accounted for only 11 percent (Fankhauser R L. et al.
Molecular Epidemiology of "Norwalk-like Viruses" in Outbreaks of
Gastroenteritis in the United Statescfn1. Journal Infect Dis 1998;178:1571-1578
<http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/JID/journal/issues/v178n6/980618/980618.text.html#fn1#fn1>).
In a MEDLINE search for recent hospital outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis
in the U.S. I found only one report, in which nurses visiting their
colleague who was hospitalized with acute viral gastroenteritis were
implicated in the outbreak (Caceres VM et al, A viral gastroenteritis
outbreak associated with person-to-person spread among hospital staff.
Infect Control Hosp Epidemiol 1998 Mar;19(3):162-7). In California in the
past 10 years, reports of nursing home outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis
have been common while none have been reported in acute care hospitals.
Assuming this difference is real, I welcome ProMED subscribers' comments on
the possible reasons. I would not expect basic infection control
precautions such as hand washing to differ dramatically. In questioning
colleagues, differences in admission rates and hospital ward structure have
been offered as possibilities.
--
Jon Rosenberg, M.D.
California Department of Health Services
Division of Communicable Disease Control
Infection Control and Healthcare Epidemiology
Berkeley CA
<jrosenbe@dhs.ca.gov>
