Date: Sat 2 Nov 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source IC Surrey on Line, Sutton and Epsom Advertiser, Sat 2 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://icsurreyonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0200surreyheadlines/page.cfm?objectid=12330837&method=full&siteid=53340>

England: Virus outbreak Causes Admissions Crisis at Epsom Hospital
--------------------------------------------------
New patients are being turned away from wards after a winter vomiting virus
swept through troubled Epsom Hospital. Patients on 4 wards at the hospital
in Dorking Road, Epsom have been struck down by the [virus]. Managers have
been forced to close affected wards off to newcomers to stop the virus
spreading further. This is bad news for the hospital where the number of
patients coming in is already limited by the number of beds being occupied
by patients waiting for social services care to be arranged before being
discharged. The Alex and Croft ward, 2 bays on the Britten ward, and a bay
on the Buckley ward have all been hit by the vomiting virus, but none of
the patients in the affected areas will be moved.
Dr Lindy Stevens, medical director at Epsom and St Helier NHS Trust,
explained that although the virus is unpleasant, it is very rarely
dangerous and the symptoms normally pass within 24 and 48 hours. She said:
"We are temporarily not introducing new patients to these areas so that the
virus can be isolated. The situation is now improving and is being reviewed
on a daily basis. We anticipate that the affected areas will be able to
accept new patients by the end of the week." But while the infection is
kept under control, friends and relatives of patients on the affected wards
are being asked to keep their visits brief and to keep contact to a
minimum. Dr Stevens added: "However, we would like to stress that it is
business as usual and we will still continue to admit patients via accident
and emergency and for planned operations."
An estimated one million people in Britain fall foul of the effects of the
virus every year, although most incidents are not reported to doctors or
health officials. Winter is usually high season for the virus because
people are more confined indoors in smoky, stuffy or crowded environments.
A spokesperson for the Public Health Laboratory Service, which monitors the
levels of such viruses, said: "Cases are going up but that is what we would
expect to see at this time of year."
[Byline: Karen Styan]
